e preferred on empirical grounds over approaches that depend on an enrichment of the syntactic apparatus. Dynamics of Meaning illustrates how seemingly abstract stances on the nature of meaning can have significant and far-reaching linguistic consequences, leading to the detection of new facts and influencing our understanding of the syntax/semantics/pragmatics interface.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLanguage and languages. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  agrammar, linguistics, semantics, quantification, presupposition, anaphora, interpretation, indefinites, e-type strategy, syntactic theory, reconstruction effects, weak crossover, syntax, pragmatics, logic, discourse, topicalization, definites, sequence, emphasis, meaning, reference, truth, human systems, philosophy, language.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226104515423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226104515/original  a978-3-11-066785-1  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles